Lab From A Chip is a DIY intervention in lab-on-a-chip technology inspired by science and technology studies (STS) and microbiological technique. It's part of Ross Dalziel's PhD research project, Critical Kits at the Division for BioMedical Life Sciences at Lancaster University (BLS) and makerspace DoESLiverpool using the Foldscope, a folding paper microscope by Prakash Labs.
"A lab-on-a-chip is a device that integrates one or several laboratory functions on a single integrated circuit of only millimeters to a few square centimeters" Wikipedia

It packages up a review of bio-technology and microbiological technique - the material practices of doing bio-science. We've packaged up an existing, friendly cheap accessible microscope, the Foldscope; and an innovative practice of scientist Alexandre Benedetto and his colleagues at BLS.

They make cheap robust consistent PDMS microfluidic channels to watch nematode worms using old vinyl audio records as moulds. We make a DIY version of the process for you to follow using vinyl fragments, surplus electronics and Euglena gracilis, a light sensitive algae.
Lab From A Chip:
Foldscope Add-Ons
Inject equal amounts (0.5ml) of silicon from syringe A and fixer from syringe B into the 'floor' your mini petri dish (it's the smaller diameter part)
Mix well
and add lid
Assemble your DIY paperfuge and carefully spin to get a nice thin layer.
This is optional as it's not really very effecive, but it lets us follow the practices of the technique in the lab.

Now setup your phone with the Foldscope and see if our algal friends have found their way into our microfluidic channels. We've found that the vinyl record technique is the most rewarding, as you get to see our Euglena gracilis moving along the grooves; and understand their scale compared to yours. With your phone setup you could try shining the LED included and see how they respond.

These organisms are mixotrophic in that they 'eat' proteins and plant matter but also photosynthesise, so like plants 'make' food from sunlight. In a way they are like plants but also behave like animals.

Have a think what other ordinary stuff we have in our homes and workplaces that might have tiny spaces the size of record grooves or silicon chip logos? What about textiles? The surface of your phone or pair of running shoes/trainers/sneakers? An old pair of headphones? The surface of some wood or steel? Your mobile phone? Once you put yourself in the Algae's position the human engineered world and all it's 'freedoms' becomes vast and almost terrifying in it's scale and impact while we find it easy to forget and make this invisible.
